The diagram uses a graphical representation to show how different components are related to one another and how they interact within the system. It seems to be part of a technical document or manual that is providing guidance on configuring an OPC UA-based industrial automation system, specifically focusing on aggregates and their associated functions and capabilities.

Description: This image appears to be a photograph of a mathematical figure, which looks like a screenshot from a presentation or a digital document. The figure seems to illustrate a concept related to statistics, specifically standard deviation in a population context.

In the center of the image is a horizontal bar with a label that reads "StandardDeviationPopulation." The data presented seems to be related to some kind of measurement or scoring system, where each value x_i is associated with a weighting factor (denoted as w_i), which contributes to the calculation of the average in the expression on the right. The use of the sigma symbol (∑) implies that this is an iterative summation over all values in the dataset.

The image has a watermark or overlay text at the bottom that reads "OPC and OPC UA," which suggests that the document may be related to the Open Platform Communication (OPC) standard for industrial interoperability, as indicated by the acronym "OPC." This context implies that the figure might be part of a technical or engineering discussion on how these statistical measures are applied in real-time systems or data analysis within an industrial setting.

The specific mathematical equations and symbols, such as the average formula (∑(w_i * x_i) / Σ(w_i)), imply that this is a standard deviation calculation, which is a measure of dispersion or how much individual data points differ from the mean in a dataset. The figure is likely being used to explain the mathematical steps involved in calculating standard deviation for a population, rather than just a sample.

Overall, the image provides a technical and numerical illustration that would be more informative in a professional or academic context related to data analysis, statistics, and industrial processes or standards.
